# Advanced Economics O/X
> Core principles of micro and macro economics
// Swiq — https://swiq.jiun.dev/set/seed.en.economy-finance.principles/

According to the law of demand, all else equal, when the price of a good rises its quantity demanded tends to fall. | O | The law of demand states that higher prices generally reduce the quantity demanded.
Inflation is a general and sustained increase in prices that reduces the purchasing power of money. | O | Inflation erodes purchasing power as the same money buys fewer goods over time.
Opportunity cost is the combined value of every alternative given up, not just the next-best one. | X | Opportunity cost is the value of the single next-best alternative forgone, not the sum of all alternatives.
Raising the central bank's key interest rate generally tends to cool borrowing, spending, and investment. | O | Higher rates raise borrowing costs, which tends to slow spending and investment.
GDP measures the market value of final goods and services produced within a country over a period. | O | GDP sums the market value of final output produced within a nation's borders in a period.
In a monopoly, many firms compete so that no single firm can influence the price. | X | A monopoly has a single dominant supplier that can influence price; many-firm competition is the opposite.
Supply and demand determine the equilibrium price where quantity supplied equals quantity demanded. | O | At equilibrium the quantity supplied equals the quantity demanded, setting the market price.
Deflation is a sustained fall in the general price level. | O | Deflation is a sustained decrease in prices, which can discourage spending and deepen slumps.
What policy tool does a central bank use to manage inflation by adjusting interest rates and money supply? | 1)Monetary policy 2)Fiscal policy 3)Trade policy 4)Industrial policy | 1 | Monetary policy is run by a central bank to manage money supply, interest rates, and inflation.
Which term describes goods that tend to be bought less as consumer income rises? | 1)Inferior goods 2)Luxury goods 3)Normal goods 4)Public goods | 1 | Demand for inferior goods falls as income rises, unlike normal or luxury goods.
Q: What is the government's use of taxation and spending to influence the economy called? (two words) | A: fiscal policy | Fiscal policy uses government taxing and spending to influence aggregate demand and the economy.
Q: What term describes a general, sustained rise in prices that reduces money's value? | A: inflation | Inflation is a sustained increase in the general price level that lowers purchasing power.
